### Access Runtime Environment Variables in Next.js App Router

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/environment-variables.mdx

These examples demonstrate how to securely access non-public environment variables at runtime within the Next.js App Router. By using dynamic rendering features like `connection` or other dynamic APIs (e.g., `cookies`, `headers`), the environment variable `MY_VALUE` is evaluated at request time on the server, ensuring its value is up-to-date.

```tsx
import { connection } from 'next/server'

export default async function Component() {
  await connection()
  // cookies, headers, and other Dynamic APIs
  // will also opt into dynamic rendering, meaning
  // this env variable is evaluated at runtime
  const value = process.env.MY_VALUE
  // ...
}
```

```jsx
import { connection } from 'next/server'

export default async function Component() {
  await connection()
  // cookies, headers, and other Dynamic APIs
  // will also opt into dynamic rendering, meaning
  // this env variable is evaluated at runtime
  const value = process.env.MY_VALUE
  // ...
}
```

--------------------------------

### Use connection() function for runtime environment variable access

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/upgrading/version-16.mdx

Call the connection() function before reading from process.env to ensure environment variables are read at runtime rather than bundled at build time. This is useful for dynamic configuration that may change between deployments.

```typescript
// app/page.tsx
import { connection } from 'next/server'

export default async function Page() {
  await connection()
  const config = process.env.RUNTIME_CONFIG
  return <p>{config}</p>
}
```

### Runtime Environment Variables > App Router Implementation

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/environment-variables.mdx

In the App Router, you can safely read environment variables on the server during dynamic rendering by using the `connection()` function from `next/server`. When you call `await connection()` in a server component, it opts into dynamic rendering, meaning environment variables are evaluated at runtime rather than build time. This approach, along with other Dynamic APIs like cookies and headers, allows your application to access environment variables that may differ across deployment environments.

--------------------------------

### Runtime Environment Variables > Overview

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/environment-variables.mdx

Next.js supports both build time and runtime environment variables. By default, environment variables are only available on the server. To expose an environment variable to the browser, it must be prefixed with `NEXT_PUBLIC_`, but these public variables will be inlined into the JavaScript bundle during the build. For runtime environment variables that need to be evaluated at request time rather than build time, you can read them safely on the server during dynamic rendering, allowing you to use a single Docker image that can be promoted through multiple environments with different values.

--------------------------------

### Runtime Configuration

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/upgrading/version-16.mdx

`serverRuntimeConfig` and `publicRuntimeConfig` have been removed. Developers should now use environment variables instead. For server-only values, environment variables can be accessed directly in Server Components. To prevent accidentally passing sensitive server values to Client Components, developers can use the [taint API](/docs/app/api-reference/config/next-config-js/taint). For values that need to be accessible on the client side, the `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix should be used with environment variables. Additionally, to ensure environment variables are read at runtime rather than being bundled at build time, the [`connection()`](/docs/app/api-reference/functions/connection) function should be used before reading from `process.env`.

### Access Environment Variables in Next.js App Router Route Handler

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/environment-variables.mdx

This snippet illustrates accessing server-side environment variables (from `.env`) within a Route Handler in the Next.js App Router. Route Handlers act as API endpoints, and environment variables are essential for secure server-side operations like database connections.

```js
export async function GET() {
  const db = await myDB.connect({
    host: process.env.DB_HOST,
    username: process.env.DB_USER,
    password: process.env.DB_PASS,
  })
  // ...
}
```

--------------------------------

### Fetch data with API key in TypeScript and JavaScript

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/01-getting-started/05-server-and-client-components.mdx

A server-side function that fetches data from an external service using an API key stored in environment variables. This function should never be exposed to the client, as it contains sensitive credentials. The function demonstrates the risk of environment poisoning when imported into Client Components.

```typescript
export async function getData() {
  const res = await fetch('https://external-service.com/data', {
    headers: {
      authorization: process.env.API_KEY,
    },
  })

  return res.json()
}
```

```javascript
export async function getData() {
  const res = await fetch('https://external-service.com/data', {
    headers: {
      authorization: process.env.API_KEY,
    },
  })

  return res.json()
}
```

### Environment Variables > Bundling Environment Variables for the Browser

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/environment-variables.mdx

To bundle environment variables for the browser, you must prefix them with `NEXT_PUBLIC_`. This convention tells Next.js which variables should be exposed to the client-side code. Only variables with the `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix will be included in the browser bundle, while other variables remain server-only. This security feature ensures that sensitive information like API keys and database credentials are not accidentally exposed to the client.

--------------------------------

### Security > Passing Data from Server to Client

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/data-security.mdx

On the initial load, both Server and Client Components run on the server to generate HTML, but they execute in isolated module systems. This ensures that Server Components can access private data and APIs, while Client Components cannot. Server Components run only on the server and can safely access environment variables, secrets, databases, and internal APIs. Client Components run on the server during pre-rendering but must follow the same security assumptions as code running in the browser, and must not access privileged data or server-only modules. This architecture ensures the app is secure by default, though it's possible to accidentally expose private data through how data is fetched or passed to components.

--------------------------------

### Data fetching and caching > Route Handlers

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/production-checklist.mdx

Route Handlers in Next.js serve as a bridge for Client Components to access backend resources without exposing sensitive information to the browser. However, Route Handlers should not be called from Server Components, as this creates an unnecessary additional server request. Proper usage of Route Handlers maintains security while enabling client-side components to interact with your backend infrastructure.

